<br>
After reading through this whole thread, I have to chuckle. I've seen so many of these situations. When I first started playing EQ, I had a warrior. He's been parked since level 35. When I decided I was sick and tired of begging SoW's and buffs everywhere I went, I began a shammy who is now my main. It would be impossible for me to even estimate the number of SoW's I have cast over my shammy's career. And the new rage is the Harnessing of Spirit buff. People don't seem to realize HoS sucks 425 mana on each cast, so they act surprised when I respond I am OOM. As a general rule, I never say "no" to any request for a SoW or a buff or a heal. Heck, most heals I initiate when I notice someone needs a little help. But things must have changed at some point. I remember at level 9, almost everyone who received a SoW offered to donate. Those who were cash poor would even apologize for not being able to donate. For a long time now, I don't charge for any buff or SoW and turn down donations when offered. But I do notice the people who seem to think I live only to serve them with buffs and SoWs. They go on my list of undesirables who get turned away the next time they demand something.<br>
<br>
When did the game dynamic change so that people EXPECT the buffers, SoWers, healers, corpse summoners, teleporters to serve them as if we were some sort of maid or butler? I think I've been far too nice giving out whatever someone asks/ demands/ expects. What if the casting enhancers among us started walking the picket line? When they send tell to us and expect us to come running to them, it's time to tell them to piss off. And the bloody beggars - oh, don't get me started. New players seem to think I have all sorts of high level weapons and armor in bags, carrying it around on me, just waiting for a chance to twink some n00b. When I started my characters I had only the wimpy little weapon or spell and 5 foods and 5 waters and a book of discord. I didn't get twinked, I earned what I have the old fashion way, by time and effort and investment of myself.<br>
<br>
OK, enough of the negative stuff for now. I do want to say that I have come across some extremely wonderful people in game. When I was working on part of my epic, I came across a group of people on 5 January who helped me kill the Black Dire Wolf, which helped me reach the two-third point on my epic. Many thanks goes to:<br>
<br>
Milander Truewield of Fallen Friends<br>
Salenie Mithrilweaver of Clan Battle Axe<br>
Eljefe Mariaci of Cries of Insurrection<br>
Aeonn of Vivix Protectorate<br>
Svenghali (guild unknown)<br>
Granamir (guild unknown)<br>
<br>
I had gone into Mistmoore just to scout out what I needed to do for when I brought a group back in to help me, but they offered to assist and it sped me along my way much faster than I had expected. I'll never forget your kindness.<br>
<br>
And recently I must thank a 54 cleric who dropped what she was doing to travel three zones to rez my two fallen guildmates. Two of my guildmates, Twap and Ceathorn, had helped me on the Qeynos Badge of Honor quest. As a result, they both died and I was just a sliver of health when I finally took down a 55 SK mob. Sindarenee, the cleric, came when I sent tell to her asking for help. I was a stranger, but I did ask respectively and offer to donate any price. She came and rezzed my friends and then turned down my offer of 200pp. I can only hope to aspire to her level of compassion and quality.<br>
<br>
So, there are true heroes involved in EQ. They mostly go unsung and unnoticed. But every act of kindness builds upon the next. I am a better person as a result and my game experience is that much more enhanced because of it. It is that feeling that I hope we all try to pass on to others in game. And I hope those reading this thread who have taken advantage of the casters who can enhance their characters, will stop and think just how much better the support if they simply showed a bit more respect and gratitude.<br>
<br>
Seanchans<br>
51 Shaman<br>
Guild Master, Inner Circle of Norrath<br>
http://www.eqicon.com<br>
<br>
